This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with spoken dialogue systems and their strategies for preventing, identifying and repairing problems that arise in the conversation. It also involves the use of natural language processing techniques to automatically train a problematic dialogue predictor. 

It could also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as the paper involves the use of machine learning algorithms to train the predictor. 

Additionally, it could belong to cs.SD (Sound) as it deals with spoken dialogue systems and their use of audio input and output. 

It could also belong to cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) as it involves the study of how humans interact with computer systems through spoken dialogue. 

Finally, it could belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it involves the use of machine learning algorithms to train the predictor.
